This experiment designed to study emotional regulation in 15-month-olds.
â£
While the results of this experiment show how toddlers regulate their behaviour based on adult cues, it also demonstrates how deeply babies are affected by anger - even when itâs not directed at them.
â£
ð¥ Babies can read facial expressions and tone
ð¥ Their stress response activates in the brain
ð¥ And they stop playing, exploring, engaging
â£
ð§  When exposed to adult anger, a babyâs amygdala (the brainâs fear center) becomes more reactive.
Repeated exposure can rewire how they respond to stress -

â£
This is why I have a rule: no one shouts around my baby.

Because this is baby development in action.
What they see, feel, and hear becomes the blueprint for how safe the world feels.

Baby development doesnât just happen through play - itâs shaped by the emotional environment we create.
â£
Protecting their development means protecting their environment.

Tag that penguinð­

Penguins are often seen as adorable and social birds, but in extreme situations, they can exhibit unusual and disturbing behaviors, including cannibalism. While not a natural or common trait among penguins, there have been recorded cases where environmental pressures, food scarcity, or stress have led to such incidents. Some penguins, particularly in harsh Antarctic conditions, have been observed consuming dead chicks or eggs, likely as a desperate survival mechanism. Unlike predatory birds, penguins do not typically prey on their own kind, making these cases rare and largely situational.

One of the most well-known reports of strange penguin behavior comes from British explorer Dr. George Murray Levick in the early 1900s. While studying AdÃ©lie penguins, he observed aggressive mating behavior, egg destruction, and rare instances of adult penguins attacking or eating chicks. Some penguins have also been known to steal eggs from other nests, sometimes breaking them and consuming the contents. While this may not be true cannibalism in the strictest sense, it suggests that competition for resources can drive penguins to behaviors that seem shocking to human observers.

Despite these rare cases, penguins are primarily social creatures that rely on cooperation within their colonies to survive. Cannibalistic behaviors are generally seen only in extreme situations, such as food shortages or highly stressful environments. In normal circumstances, penguins show strong parental instincts and care for their young diligently. The few documented instances of cannibalism serve as a reminder of how nature can push animals to unexpected extremes when survival is at stake.
